# Lambda Handler Conventions

## Handler Structure

```typescript
import type { APIGatewayProxyEvent, APIGatewayProxyResult } from 'aws-lambda';

export const handler = async (event: APIGatewayProxyEvent): Promise<APIGatewayProxyResult> => {
  try {
    // 1. Parse and validate input (use Zod)
    // 2. Execute business logic via service layer
    // 3. Return formatted response
    return { statusCode: 200, body: JSON.stringify(result) };
  } catch (error) {
    // Structured error logging, then return error response
  }
};
```

## Rules
- Handlers are thin: parse input, call service, format output
- Business logic lives in `backend/src/services/`, never in handlers
- Validate all input with Zod schemas at handler entry
- Always return proper CORS headers via a shared `response` utility
- Log structured JSON (no console.log of raw objects)
- Use environment variables for resource names (`TABLE_NAME`, `BUCKET_NAME`), never hardcode

## Error Handling
- Catch all errors at handler level
- Map known errors to appropriate HTTP status codes
- Return `500` with generic message for unexpected errors
- Always log the full error before returning
